We were promised freedom in this beautiful country. The right to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. The government should not have to care for us from cradle to grave. That should not be the role of a government, but it should be the role of the people. Take for instance healthcare. The government's role in one's life should be to ensure freedom and liberty. But healthcare should be our own responsibility. And for those who cannot care for themselves, through no fault of their own, should be cared for by their fellow man, out of human decency, out of humanity, out of love. Before we had government healthcare and all the bureaucracy that followed with it, how did the poor obtain healthcare in the United States? Obamacare is the most recent reform of the healthcare system in America.  Originally,  President Obama called for a single-payer system (similar to what Bernie wants), but that did not receive sufficient political support at the time.  Obamacare is offered through private insurance companies, but the states can set up insurance exchanges in order to try to get better rates and it became illegal to deny people health coverage on account of pre-existing medical conditions.  Additionally, young people were allowed to stay on their parents health plans until they were 26 years old.


Obamacare extended healthcare to millions of people who lacked it previously, and was a major step forward, but it is still flawed.  Prescription drug prices continue to rise rapidly (though the rate of increase has slowed somewhat), and since the insurance is still private it still becomes "for people who can afford it" after a point.  Also, the degree of state control over the program meant that many Republican governors, who opposed Obamacare (and most of whatever else the President did) were able to obstruct aspects of the program's operation in their states, such as the establishment of the health insurance exchanges.


Bernie was one of the authors of the final Obamacare law, but he had wanted more ambitious reforms, such as single payer (the government takes over the role of the health insurance companies, though private insurance may still exist for those who want it), and he is trying to rally support for said reforms during his presidential campaign.  He wants to make access to  healthcare a fundamental right of all citizens, to be paid for with modestly increased taxes on the middle class and substantially higher taxes on the wealthy and stock market speculation.

Berniecare is essentially a monopsony: a single buyer environment that results in lower prices. In this case, the only buyer is the government. Of course this will lower healthcare costs for people. Walter Ruiz
We are limited to what we have, but the crazy thing - and I say this from personal experience - is the resources we have, compared to what we tend to think we have. Our imaginations are notoriously great at ideas, but they're poor at grasping onto details and while the common trope is to think that our imagination's detail limitations is working against us... sometimes it's just the opposite. Sometimes we vastly underestimate the resources at our disposal precisely because our imaginations are so limited in seeing the details.

That's where the "dreams can come true" trope is born from. Not from our imagination itself, but from the experience of seeing in detail what human strength can accomplish, sometimes above and beyond our wildest dreams.

But I understand the limitations of reality. When I drive my car, I don't expect it to drive myself. And I know that no president's stay in office will last forever. But I believe in the power of perspective for making progress; I believe in showing people what can be accomplished - showing them how much untapped and unused potential is rotting away useless in a bin. It's why I support Obama's efforts on health care, even if I'm not in love with the exact application of it; he fought hard and showed this country that government health care is more than something "other countries do." It can be real here. People like Bernie, MLK, and Elizabeth Cady Stanton didn't get their message across instantly and they didn't make progress instantly. They aren't wizards and I don't expect wizardy. But what they all have in common is that they stuck to a cause for the people and by the people throughout their lives, in the face of opposition.

That kind of tenacity for rights and freedoms isn't a thing you can manufacture around a strategic campaign table because campaigns don't last a lifetime. I don't expect Bernie to solve all of the country's problems if he gets elected; I expect him to remind this country what grassroots tenacity and democracy look like. And he already has done that with his campaign. It's just a question of how much further he can take it. And how far he can take it will forever be helped along by the people who stand beside him as a community.

Bernie, like MLK, like Elizabeth Cady Stanton, like countless other activists of their time, are unwavering figureheads who make history, but nothing is stronger than the support of the people who back them. Their true strength is in being the rock in a tempestuous sea.

They remind us that we don't have to let the political sea buffet us around. We can do something about it. I've never thought of myself as a patriot, but I tell you, the USA is a country that has space for grassroots efforts and the value of that is immeasurable.

That is like comparing a male engineers' salary to a female elementary school teachers' salary. There has been research done (Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis) that shows that women earn about 95% of what a man earns for the same job. The other 5% wage gap is caused by two factors. The second is that women are more often than not the primary nurturers of a families children. They are not able to fully commit to their work whereas men can do so more often.
That leaves leaves only a slim possibility that women have lower wages due to gender discrimination.

Honest question for people in favor of raising minimum wage: Do you think big businesses will be tremendously effected and have to raise prices in order to be sustainable, or will it be the small businesses that suffer, the family owned business that will have to raise prices in order to remain profitable and in turn be less competitive?

+Joshua Bribiesca technically both should happen. The real problem we are seen is that prices are going up anyway and people are getting priced out of being able to afford living. I am a 23 y.o. software engineer making a healthy amount of money annually. Regardless I will never be able to afford a house as things stand. I really cannot imagine how people making 1/2 of what I make with 20K student loans manage to survive.  I originally come from very low income and my mother still lives in a poorer area. Even there the cost of living and food is increasing to levels far beyond the wages provided in the area. It is clear to me that if I want my mother to not live in a garage I will have to subsidize her living for the rest of her life. How are other people going to manage this? Mind you I do have high skill career but no one should live in a tiny box if they are working 40 hours a week.


Now about business owners. yes it will have an impact on them. First big companies. You should probably look at workers more in terms of production and hours of work each body provides. If big companies need 400,000 hours a week of work they better hire 400,000 hours of work. Cutting people will likely cut profits as production and dissatisfaction increases unless they were already saturated. It will make investors gain less but workers gain more. It does however, impact small business owners negatively, particularly a small business trying to take off that hired quite some people it can barely afford.  That said it should be pointed out that said workers being paid minimum wage are already living a sub-par existence so we are already in a less than ideal situation. This is basically bargaining for the  quality of life of the business owners vs that of the employees.


This anecdotal evidence, but I personally never met a business owner with employees under him/her that is not living in a far better economic position than the employees. I don't think business owners should be in prop 8 housing but it is clear that favoring their quality of life over the employees is not working for our economy. I think it is time to shift the wealth downwards somewhat toward the working people because that trickle-down economic theory that has been in effect for decades is wiping out our middle class.

Steve Harvey¬†I never claimed to be neutral. I imagine that a neutral being can't muster up a reason to feed himself. You're trying to pass yourself off as a man of reason. What I mean by abstract is some sense of thought like an intuition or a pattern, which doesn't explicitly have a connection with the intended medium.

Logic is mostly used as a meme which means something like: comprehensive, exact, without holes. However, I see it as a patterned way of thinking, intended to be consistent instead of comprehensive. So that it may be used to describe many different objects in the same language. It's usefulness is tied to the number of things it describes. That way references and relationships between the objects one is being logical about can be consistent.

Hypothetically, if a logic was complete it would have truth, but that isn't the case for humans. We vary with time and our biological state, so not one of us is logical in its pure sense. So when you suggest that you are being logical and I am not, I have good reason to doubt you. Moreover, the complexity, and breadth of your logic is as yet unstated.

There's nothing morally grey about my position; it simply balances an identification o f the ideals to be pursued with the requirements in the real world for realizing them, rather than¬†pretend that idealism divorced of any analysis, divorced of any mobilization of precise knowledge of the systemic realities of the world, existing in an emotionally self-gratifying but utterly impotent vacuum sufficient to¬†create the happy illusion of¬†moral superiority but capable only of being exploited by those¬†less absurd for ends utterly unrelated to those¬†for which they are held in the first place.¬†This has nothing to do with¬† "impartiality"; it has to do with applying disciplined reason and imagination to the challenges we face, in order to face them most effectively. You arrogate to yourself a pretense of superiority for eschewing such disciplined reason in favor of a cartoonish reduction of reality, which is sufficient to satisfy your needs but insufficient to accomplish anything in the real world.¬†

As for logic, it is what it is, and I teach it. I am (or have been) a sociologist, lawyer, author, teacher, public policy consultant and social analyst who applies methodical analytical reasoning to methodically gathered and verified information in service to a rigorously derived understanding of the dynamical systems in which we are ensconced, for the purpose of navigating those systems to maximum effect in service to our shared humanity. It's really the only rational way to go about this shared endeavor we are engaged in. Now, you want to convince yourself of something else, something fluffier and more appealing to your cognitive modality, have at it. But logical argumentation will never succeed in proving why something other than logic is superior to it, or why some alternative definition of logic that merely rationalizes one's own preferred irrationality is superior to our systemic and historically developed definition of its various forms and branches.

The use of logic does not imply a claim to certainty or infallibility, but recognition of uncertainty and fallibility does not imply any diminution in the value of the use of logic. Indeed, a rational person recognizes that the world is a complex and subtle place and that humans are highly fallible, and incorporates that into their understanding. It is not a pretense of being perfectly logical, but rather an effort to use the best tools of human consciousness to the best advantage to the greatest extent possible and for the most humane and productive purposes possible. Being assiduously rational (which is not to say unimaginative or dispassionate, imagination and passion being corollaries of rather than incompatible with logic) is always preferable to being¬†self-indulgently irrational instead, if one takes seriously the responsibility to humanity that we are both claiming is motivating us in the present instance.
.
I have only skimmed your comments, including this most recent one, but it appears at a glance that you are implying that uncertainty means that arbitrary opinions are indistinguishable in value from more diligently derived ones, or that a vague heuristic methodology is as reliable as a more precisely defined one. I personally think that, while heuristics play a role and can be quite valuable, wherever a question can be subjected to a more rigorous analysis, the understanding of that question and the possible answers to it improves through the effort.

I have a precise analysis of why the glassy-eyed support that some seem to have for Bernie is both irrational and counterproductive. I don't think it helps to achieve the ends that motivate it; in fact, I think it contributes to a greater probability of a lesser movement in the direction of their achievement. I don't think that casually or arbitrarily or because I have some emotional predisposition which motivates me to, but rather because my own careful consideration of available evidence sifted through the organizing process of rational analysis leads me to that conclusion. I can and have written at length in various places exactly what evidence and what rational analysis applied to it leads to that conclusion. And I would certainly respect and entertain a similarly rigorous counterargument, but that is, so far, not what I have encountered. Instead, I encounter various defenses of irrationality and arbitrary belief. I do not believe that they are really quite so defensible.

Political skills and expertise involves the ability, first, to assess the various probabilities of various outcomes as determined by all of the poltical variables currently in place, including the composition of Congress, the demographic and partisan map of the country (including enough districts gerrymandered to be safely ultra-conservative to block any of the legislation that Bernie favors), the ideological composition of the country and the current zeitgeist, and which variables are in motion in which directions with what possible trajectories depending on what set of factors. That is just a fraction of the complex dynamical reality that must be constantly assessed and reassessed, with empirical and analytical.

Then, one must be able to assess the configurations of interests embedded in that landscape, including the interests of all relevant office holders, the interests of their constituents, the interests of other groups with varying kinds and degrees of political economic, organizational, and cultural power. One must know enough about the other systemic phenomena that intersect that social institutional and technological landscape to understand how policies affect them, sometimes in counterintuitive ways, and how those effects impact the various interests in complex and tangled relationships to one another. Finally, one must be able to engage in a set of bargaining, trading, cajoling, and other strategic interactions to achieve tangible outcomes that best serve the agenda that that individual has "hitched their star" to.

The kinds of politicians who the zealots in both parties condemn as tainted and corrupt are frequently those with precisely these skills, to varying degrees. (It is usually more heuristic than how I've presented it, much as a billiards player uses complex physical dynamics embedded in techniques rather than expressed academically). The kinds of politicians who the zealots in both parties embrace as representing the kind of purity they long for are generally, sometimes cynically and sometimes genuinely, the kind who simply don't have those skills and talents but say what those populist factions want to hear and play on their naivete.

Those who promise things through elected office that are not realistically attainable at present through that aspect of our process are not offering a positive change but rather a self-destructive diversion of energy into that which can't be done, and by doing so are sacrificing that which can be done. Those who choose officials solely on the basis of how much they agree with what they say are privileging the cheapest dimension of a complex package over other essential dimensions that are more prosaic but far more necessary.

(On the other hand, Bernie as the leader of a movement working to change the zeitgeist so that, years down the line, we could attain the kinds of policy shifts he favors, would be great. Two useful places where he could do that most effectively is as a social movement leader operating outside the realm of electoral politics, or in a cabinet position, Secretary of Labor, for instance, where his skills and passions would be put to best use.)

I have nothing against Bernie, but the description above of a savvy politician is not at all of him. In fact, the things that his supporters love most about him is the degree to which he is "above that fray," the only problem being that no political ends can be accomplished by being above that fray. Bernie has had a very unspectacular legislative career, because he is much more talented at articulating an intelligent and appealing ideological narrative than at accomplishing anything in the political arena.

It is often said that candidates campaign in poetry and govern in prose. That means that wise voters try to see through the poetry to discover if that candidate also has a particularly deft ability with the more prosaic demands of effective governance. Bernie has not demonstrated any such ability to any great degree.

The mistake many make is the belief that the ultimate political arena is electoral politics, and that if electoral politics isn't the place where our highest ideals can be most directly and uncompromisingly pursued, then the hell with it. But electoral politics is the most immediate and superficial dimension of political action, while the more essential and fundamental political struggle is a cultural one. It is not necessary, therefore, to eschew electoral politics because it isn't what it isn't, nor to abandon one's deeper ideals because electoral politics isn't the venue in which they can be most directly and uncompromisingly pursued. Rather, we should invest in the necessary and messy and only ever partially successful struggles in the electoral political arena with pragmatism and realistic expectations, and invest in more unfettered and ambitious struggles in the cultural arena.

Three, there is a combination of continuity and discontinuity; the notion of there either being or not being "a collective" is a false dichotomy. It essentially is sort of a soft corporate fascism.  

Economic neoliberalism is the economic philosophy that the government should not tax the super rich and corporations much, and that it should also hand out massive amounts of money to the rich and those same corporations.  They all now have either moved overseas and or practice profit models that depend upon this kind of market CONTROL.  

Ironically these same people fund the media sources that tell the tale of the "free market"- never mind the fact that their very business models are dependent upon government handouts, market controls in their favor, and cronyism.  For example the fossil fuels industry gets about 5.3 trillion dollars a year in government subsidy from world governments.  This is more than ALL past yearly US government revenues, and it is about 1/3 of the entire US GDP.

Meanwhile as the government takes in less revenues the public sector takes all the cuts decade after decade.  The very same public sector that is mostly responsible for the lion's share of advancements in science and technology.   So this is why really the right and the left both have politicians that are bought and are out to serve the moneyed interests.   

So there is NO perfect solution, but Bernie is the best solution because he will go back to a more traditional sustainable tax and investment plan and more traditional economic planning by way of investing in the public sector and private contracts to drive up employment and wages at the local and state levels thereby driving up wage based consumerism which is what should ideally drive small businesses etc.  

I mean Bernie is the only candidate that has promised NOT to put someone from a big bank as the national secretary of the treasury.  

If you look at FDR and Eisenhower, epitome left and right politicians from the 1950s and earlier- both of them taxed the rich and reinvested the money back into the public sector and private contracting.   Thereby creating a more sustainable hyperinflation cycle- one that feeds common prosperity not just the prosperity of the top 5%.

Currently we have another kind of hyper inflation cycle which is called a "vicious cycle"- it basically siphons most of the money to the top and leads to the lessening of the qualities of life for most while enriching a few using government controls.  In the long run it is bad for everyone involved.

Beyond this we have to reestablish JUSTICE in the US.  Those bankers that intentionally caused the crash should all be put in jail and or be put to working on a more sustainable way of making profits.  And the justice system needs to be redesigned to stop putting so many americans in jail for minor possession, and those people should be put to work by way of investing in the working class in the public and private contracting sector.
